<doc id="74361" wikidata="Q863510" url="?curid=74361" title="Binary symmetric channel">
<text>A binary symmetric channel (or BSCp) is a common communications channel model used in coding theory and information theory. In this model, a transmitter wishes to send a bit (a zero or a one), and the receiver will receive a bit. The bit will be &quot;flipped&quot; with a &quot;crossover probability&quot; of &quot;p&quot;, and otherwise is received correctly. This model can be applied to varied communication channels such as telephone lines or disk drive storage.

The noisy-channel coding theorem applies to BSCp, saying that information can be transmitted at any rate up to the channel capacity with arbitrarily low error. The channel capacity is formula_1 bits, where formula_2 is the binary entropy function. Codes including Forney&#x27;s code have been designed to transmit information efficiently across the channel.

== Definition ==

A binary symmetric channel with crossover probability formula_3, denoted by BSCp, is a channel with binary input and binary output and probability of error formula_3. That is, if formula_5 is the transmitted random variable and formula_6 the received variable, then the channel is characterized by the conditional probabilities:

:formula_7

It is assumed that formula_8. If formula_9, then the receiver can swap the output (interpret 1 when it sees 0, and vice versa) and obtain an equivalent channel with crossover probability formula_10.

== Capacity ==

The channel capacity of the binary symmetric channel, in bits, is:
:formula_11
where formula_12 is the binary entropy function, defined by:
:formula_13

== Noisy-channel coding theorem ==
Shannon&#x27;s noisy-channel coding theorem gives a result about the rate of information that can be transmitted through a communication channel with arbitrarily low error. We study the particular case of formula_14.

The noise formula_15 that characterizes formula_16 is a random variable consisting of n independent random bits (n is defined below) where each random bit is a formula_17 with probability formula_3 and a formula_19 with probability formula_20. We indicate this by writing &quot;formula_21&quot;.

What this theorem actually implies is, a message when picked from formula_22, encoded with a random encoding function formula_23, and sent across a noisy formula_16, there is a very high probability of recovering the original message by decoding, if formula_25 or in effect the rate of the channel is bounded by the quantity stated in the theorem. The decoding error probability is exponentially small.

===Proof===
The theorem can be proved directly with a probabilistic method. Consider an encoding function formula_26 that is selected at random. This means that for each message formula_27, the value formula_28 is selected at random (with equal probabilities). For a given encoding function formula_23, the decoding function formula_30 is specified as follows: given any received codeword formula_31, we find the message formula_32 such that the Hamming distance formula_33 is as small as possible (with ties broken arbitrarily). (formula_34 is called a maximum likelihood decoding function.)

The proof continues by showing that at least one such choice formula_35 satisfies the conclusion of theorem, by integration over the probabilities. Suppose formula_3 and formula_37 are fixed. First we show that, for a fixed formula_38 and formula_23 chosen randomly, the probability of failure over formula_14 noise is exponentially small in &quot;n&quot;. At this point, the proof works for a fixed message formula_41. Next we extend this result to work for all messages formula_41. We achieve this by eliminating half of the codewords from the code with the argument that the proof for the decoding error probability holds for at least half of the codewords. The latter method is called expurgation. This gives the total process the name &quot;random coding with expurgation&quot;.


== Converse of Shannon&#x27;s capacity theorem ==

The converse of the capacity theorem essentially states that formula_43 is the best rate one can achieve over a binary symmetric channel. Formally the theorem states:

The intuition behind the proof is however showing the number of errors to grow rapidly as the rate grows beyond the channel capacity. The idea is the sender generates messages of dimension formula_25, while the channel formula_14 introduces transmission errors. When the capacity of the channel is formula_46, the number of errors is typically formula_47 for a code of block length formula_48. The maximum number of messages is formula_49. The output of the channel on the other hand has formula_50 possible values. If there is any confusion between any two messages, it is likely that formula_51. Hence we would have formula_52, a case we would like to avoid to keep the decoding error probability exponentially small.

== Codes ==
Very recently, a lot of work has been done and is also being done to design explicit error-correcting codes to achieve the capacities of several standard communication channels. The motivation behind designing such codes is to relate the rate of the code with the fraction of errors which it can correct.

The approach behind the design of codes which meet the channel capacities of formula_53 or the binary erasure channel formula_54 have been to correct a lesser number of errors with a high probability, and to achieve the highest possible rate. Shannon&#x27;s theorem gives us the best rate which could be achieved over a formula_16, but it does not give us an idea of any explicit codes which achieve that rate. In fact such codes are typically constructed to correct only a small fraction of errors with a high probability, but achieve a very good rate. The first such code was due to George D. Forney in 1966. The code is a concatenated code by concatenating two different kinds of codes.

=== Forney&#x27;s code ===

Forney constructed a concatenated code formula_56 to achieve the capacity of the noisy-channel coding theorem for formula_14. In his code,

* The outer code formula_58 is a code of block length formula_59 and rate formula_60 over the field formula_61, and formula_62. Additionally, we have a decoding algorithm formula_63 for formula_58 which can correct up to formula_65 fraction of worst case errors and runs in formula_66 time.
* The inner code formula_67 is a code of block length formula_48, dimension formula_25, and a rate of formula_70. Additionally, we have a decoding algorithm formula_71 for formula_67 with a decoding error probability of at most formula_73 over formula_14 and runs in formula_75 time. 
For the outer code formula_58, a Reed-Solomon code would have been the first code to have come in mind. However, we would see that the construction of such a code cannot be done in polynomial time. This is why a binary linear code is used for formula_58.

For the inner code formula_67 we find a linear code by exhaustively searching from the linear code of block length formula_48 and dimension formula_25, whose rate meets the capacity of formula_14, by the noisy-channel coding theorem.

The rate formula_82 which almost meets the formula_14 capacity. We further note that the encoding and decoding of formula_84 can be done in polynomial time with respect to formula_59. As a matter of fact, encoding formula_84 takes time formula_87. Further, the decoding algorithm described takes time formula_88 as long as formula_89; and formula_90.

==== Decoding error probability ====

A natural decoding algorithm for formula_84 is to:

* Assume formula_92 
* Execute formula_63 on formula_94

Note that each block of code for formula_67 is considered a symbol for formula_58. Now since the probability of error at any index formula_97 for formula_71 is at most formula_99 and the errors in formula_14 are independent, the expected number of errors for formula_71 is at most formula_102 by linearity of expectation. Now applying Chernoff bound, we have bound error probability of more than formula_103 errors occurring to be formula_104. Since the outer code formula_58 can correct at most formula_103 errors, this is the decoding error probability of formula_84. This when expressed in asymptotic terms, gives us an error probability of formula_108. Thus the achieved decoding error probability of formula_84 is exponentially small as the noisy-channel coding theorem.

We have given a general technique to construct formula_84. For more detailed descriptions on formula_67 and formula_58 please read the following references. Recently a few other codes have also been constructed for achieving the capacities. LDPC codes have been considered for this purpose for their faster decoding time.

== Applications ==
The binary symmetric channel can model a disk drive used for memory storage: the channel input represents a bit being written to the disk and the output corresponds to the bit later being read. Error could arise from the magnetization flipping, background noise or the writing head making an error. Other objects which the binary symmetric channel can model include a telephone or radio communication line or cell division, from which the daughter cells contain DNA information from their parent cell.

This channel is often used by theorists because it is one of the simplest noisy channels to analyze. Many problems in communication theory can be reduced to a BSC. Conversely, being able to transmit effectively over the BSC can give rise to solutions for more complicated channels.

